  = section "C1 = F/V/Ṯ/Ḏ/S/Z/Š/X/Ǧ" do
    %p As in Scale IV, roots with an initial fricative consonant (excluding /h/) undergo metathesis in forms where #{template "C1"} comes in direct contact with the prefixed *t of <i>nitkatab</i>. This has already been seen on a number of verbs: #{t "νιφτούκ", "niftūk"} “hiccup” (*fūk), #{t "νίσταρ̄ατ", "nistařat"} “deceive oneself” (*sřāt), #{t "νίσταηαλ", "nistahal"} “cough” (*shāl), #{t "νιστώμ", "nistām"} “hear oneself” (*smāh), #{t "νίθτακκαλ", "niṯtəkhal"} “weigh oneself” (*ṯkhāl), and so on.

  = section "T-Assimilation" do
    %p The prefixed *t of <i>nitkatab</i> is prone to the same sorts of assimilatory phenomena as seen in Scale IV when it comes in direct contact with #{template "C1"}.
    %p When #{template "C1"} is *T or *D, the prefix will assimilate completely in these forms, resulting in a geminated (never aspirated!) consonant: *drīk “go” → #{t "νίδδαρακ", "niddarak"} “accompany, go with, go together” (not *nitdarak).
    %p When #{template "C1"} is *B or *G, the prefix will voice to *d and then lenite to *ḏ: *gann “hide” → #{t "νίδ̄γαναν", "niḏganan"} “hide oneself” (not **nitganan).
    %p When #{template "C1"} is a voiced fricative *V/*Ḏ/*Z/*Ǧ, the prefixed *t will first voice to *d and then undergo the usual fricative metathesis: *zmāy “thirsty” → #{t "νίζδαμη", "nizdamē"} “work up a thirst, become dehydrated” (not **nitzamay).
